ess(OperatingSystem.IsWindows(), \"Only runs on Windows\");\n        Assert.True(true);\n    }\n\n    [Theory]\n    [InlineData(\"feature-a\")]\n    [InlineData(\"feature-b\")]\n    public void OnlyWithFeature(string feature)\n    {\n        Assert.SkipWhen(string.IsNullOrEmpty(Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable(feature)), \"Feature not enabled\");\n        Assert.NotNull(feature);\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-d68a6419efeb4d84843846477242db32/ConditionalTests.cs."},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01UNTYZEtVRsAdPrFQKG219i","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-d68a6419efeb4d84843846477242db32/global.json","old_str":"{\n  \"test\": {\n    \"runner\": \"VSTest\"\n  }\n}","new_str":"{\n  \"test\": {\n    \"runner\": \"Microsoft.Testing.Platform\"\n  }\n}"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-d68a6419efeb4d84843846477242db32/global.json."}],"interactionId":"f7f4a0cf-ac0c-41cf-978a-8967c14ba4a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the project. Let me plan the migration from xUnit v2 to xUnit v3:\n\n1. **TestProject.csproj changes:**\n   - Replace `xunit` v2.9.3 with `xunit.v3` (the v3 package)\n   - Remove `xunit.runner.visualstudio` (v3 uses a built-in runner, projects become executables)\n   - Remove `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` (not needed for v3)\n   - Remove `Xunit.SkippableFact` (v3 has built-in skip support)\n   - Add `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` since v3 test projects are executables, and ensure the target framework is at least net6.0\n\n2. **ConditionalTests.cs changes:**\n   - The `using Xunit;` namespace stays the same, though some APIs have shifted\n   - Replace `[SkippableFact]` with `[Fact]` and use either the `Skip` parameter or `Assert.Skip()` for conditional skipping\n   - `[SkippableTheory]` becomes `[Theory]`\n   - For conditional skipping, xUnit v3 provides `Assert.SkipWhen(condition, reason)` to skip when a condition is true and `Assert.SkipUnless(condition, reason)` to skip unless a condition is met, replacing the older `Skip.If()` and `Skip.IfNot()` patterns\n\nFor the global.json configuration, xUnit v3 uses Microsoft.Testing Platform instead of VSTest, so I need to update the test runner setting accordingly. The v3 projects are actually executables that can run directly with `dotnet test`.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing the `test.runner` property in global.json is a .NET 9+ feature, and if they're targeting .NET 8, this might not even be recognized. I should probably focus on what's actually relevant for their target framework rather than getting caught up in version-specific details that may not apply.\n\nFor xUnit v3, the approach is simpler—since it's a self-contained executable using Microsoft.Testing.Platform, I can either set the runner explicitly or just remove the test configuration entirely and let the project handle it. Let me update the project file to include xUnit v3 and set the output type to executable, which is what xUnit v3 expects. Let me just try building this and see what happens with the version. I'm creating a test class that uses xUnit's skip assertions to conditionally run tests based on the operating system and environment variables. I'm adding skip assertions with appropriate reason strings for Windows-only and feature-flag scenarios. For the global.json setup with xUnit v3 on .NET 8, the Microsoft.Testing.Platform integration should work directly with `dotnet test` since xUnit v3 projects are self-contained executables.\n\nSince the `test.runner` setting in global.json isn't supported until .NET 9, I should remove that section entirely to avoid confusion—xUnit v3 will use its built-in Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner regardless.","outputTokens":3153,"requestId":"B840:71272:2F69754:32557E2:6A049570"},"id":"a3bd16fd-4a96-4f55-a73f-d5817c22e776","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:15:44.750Z","parentId":"284a0277-50c2-436b-a207-6e74262d6da1"}
